===Etymology===
{{etyl|la}} {{term|trans-|lang=la}} + {{term|vestite|lang=la}}, form of {{term|vestio|vestiō|I clothe, I dress|lang=la}} (as in English {{term|vestment|lang=en}}, {{term|vest|lang=en}}). Literally, a "cross-dresser".

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who sometimes wears [[clothes]] traditionally worn by and associated with the opposite [[sex]]; typically a male who cross-dresses occasionally by habit or compulsion.

====Usage notes====
Relatively formal (Latinate); {{term|cross-dresser|lang=en}} is more casual. Unlike {{term|cross-dress|lang=en}}, the corresponding verb {{term|transvest|lang=en}} is quite rare.

'''''Transvestite''''' should not be confused with ''[[transgender]]'' or {{term|transsexual||someone who lives as the sex opposite that of his or her birth}}. Transvestites generally have lesser or no desire to permanently change their sex, but simply enjoy being able to cross-dress from time to time.

The term should also not be confused with {{term|drag queen||A male who wears women’s clothing for public performance}}, which is specifically for performers.

